## Context

`docs/bin2` covers the terminal installer (`installers/install-linux.sh`)
— that's the developer / contributor path. This doc covers the
end-user path: a graphical installer distributed as an AppImage, with
first-run configuration handled inside the GUI before the installer
exits.

The terminal installer stays. The two paths share the same XDG layout,
the same three systemd user units, the same reuse policy, the same
underlying ag binary. They differ only in **how the user drives the
install** and **whether ag is built from source or shipped pre-built**.

### Decisions already made

| Question | Choice | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| UI toolkit | **Dioxus desktop** | Single Rust + RSX skill across installer and dashboard; reused widget patterns; one hot-reload story. |
| Distribution channel | **AppImage** | One file, no install, no maintainer accounts. Easy to add Flatpak later. |
| Build model | **Pre-built ag binaries** | Drops install time from ~30 min to ~30 sec; user doesn't need rustc / cargo / npm / trunk. The thing that actually makes Tier 4 deliver on "easier for non-CLI users." |
| First-run config | **Inside the GUI installer** | Cohesive UX — installer collects the few settings the user needs before first run; dashboard handles everything else later. |

### What the user does, end to end

```
1. Download ag-installer-vX.Y.Z-x86_64.AppImage from GitHub Releases
2. chmod +x ag-installer-*.AppImage   (or use a file manager)
3. Double-click  →  GUI opens
4. Click through screens: Welcome → Detection → Prompts → Install → First-run config → Done
5. Click "Open ag dashboard"  →  browser opens http://127.0.0.1:3010
```

Cold install on a fresh box: ~30 seconds, dominated by the file
copies + FalkorDB binary extraction + first compose-stack image
pulls (if not cached). No build step.

## What's in the AppImage

```
ag-installer-vX.Y.Z-x86_64.AppImage  (squashfs container)
├── AppRun                          (entrypoint shim)
├── ag-installer                    (Dioxus desktop binary)
├── usr/
│   ├── bin/
│   │   └── ag                      (release build of the backend, ~63 MB)
│   ├── lib/
│   │   └── libtika_native.so       (~110 MB — extractous JNI lib)
│   └── share/
│       ├── ag/
│       │   ├── web/                (frontend dist: wasm + JS, ~10 MB)
│       │   ├── falkordb/
│       │   │   ├── redis-server    (~19 MB — pre-extracted from falkordb/falkordb image)
│       │   │   ├── redis-cli       (~7 MB)
│       │   │   └── falkordb.so     (~49 MB)
│       │   ├── docker-compose.yml  (copied from repo)
│       │   ├── .env.example        (copied from repo)
│       │   └── systemd/
│       │       ├── ag.service.tmpl
│       │       ├── ag-stack.service.tmpl
│       │       ├── falkordb.service.tmpl
│       │       └── ag.service.d/
│       │           ├── falkordb.conf
│       │           └── stack.conf
│       └── applications/
│           └── ag-installer.desktop
├── ag-installer.desktop            (top-level for AppImage)
└── ag-installer.png                (top-level icon)
```

**Total AppImage size: ~270 MB** uncompressed → ~120 MB compressed
(squashfs zstd). All artifacts the bash installer would have built or
extracted are bundled, so the GUI installer's job at runtime is
**file-copy + systemd-unit-render + first-run-config**, not build +
extract.

### Pre-extracted FalkorDB — why not extract at runtime?

The bash installer pulls `falkordb/falkordb:latest` and `docker cp`s
the binaries out (~640 MB image pull + extraction). The GUI installer
pre-extracts these at AppImage build time and bundles them. Benefits:

- Installer doesn't need Docker just for FalkorDB binaries — only for
  the compose stack
- One less failure mode (musl/glibc mismatch can't surface at install
  time; we already know the bundled binaries work)
- Saves the user ~640 MB of network on first install
- AppImage is built on a known glibc baseline (Ubuntu 24.04), so
  compat is determined at build time not install time

The bundled FalkorDB version is pinned per AppImage release. Upgrading
FalkorDB = new release tag, new AppImage build.

### What's NOT bundled

- Docker itself (still a runtime dependency; same `--install-docker`
  prompt as the bash installer)
- Ollama (same — user sets it up separately, per the
  `reference-ollama-setup` memory)
- Compose stack images (grafana, loki, prometheus, tempo, otelcol,
  redis) — too big to bundle responsibly (~1.5 GB combined), and they
  already have a perfectly good distribution mechanism: `docker pull`

## Screen flow

The Dioxus desktop window opens at ~900×650 px and walks the user
through six screens, in order:

```
Welcome → Detection → Prompts → Install Progress → First-Run Config → Done
   ▲                                                                    │
   └─────────  (back navigation allowed only between Welcome           │
                and the start of Install Progress)  ◄───────────────────┘
```

Back navigation is **not allowed** once Install Progress starts —
files are being written to disk. Same one-way-after-writes promise the
bash installer makes.

### Screen 1: Welcome

Static. Branding (ag logo, version number from AppImage), one-paragraph
description of what's about to happen, and an "About what gets
installed" expand-collapse showing the XDG paths that will be written
(same as the bash installer's banner + summary preview).

Buttons: **Cancel** (closes window, no writes), **Next** (→ Detection).

### Screen 2: Detection

Runs the same detections the bash installer does, displayed as a
table with green checkmarks / yellow warning icons:

```
✓ Disk:                   22 GB free on $HOME           (≥ 20 GB recommended)
✓ Docker:                 present (28.0.1)
✓ Ollama:                 running on :11434              (8 models available)
✓ FalkorDB unit:          not present                    (will install)
✓ Compose stack:          not running                    (will start)
✓ Backend port 3010:      free
⚠ RAM:                    7 GB total                     (compose stack uses ~3 GB)
✓ Existing ag.service:    not present
```

Each row is the same detection rule as bash `detect_*` functions.
Yellow rows are "you might want to adjust" — they drive the next
screen (prompts) if they require a user choice.

Buttons: **Back**, **Next** (→ Prompts).

### Screen 3: Prompts

Conditional — only renders if Detection found something that requires
a choice. The set of possible prompts:

| Trigger | Question | Form |
|---|---|---|
| Disk 10–20 GB | "Install peaks ~3 GB on AppImage path. Continue?" | Y/N radio |
| Docker missing | "Install Docker via get.docker.com? (requires sudo)" | Y/N radio |
| Backend port busy | "Port 3010 is in use. Pick a different port:" | Number input (1024–65535) with re-validation on submit |
| Low RAM (<8 GB) | "Pick a compose profile:" | Dropdown: core (default) / observability / full / skip |
| Native obs active | "Native loki/tempo/otelcol active. Use them or compose?" | Radio: natives (default) / compose / abort |
| System Redis on 6379 | "Detected a Redis on 6379. Use it or install a parallel one?" | Radio: use system (default) / install parallel / abort |
| Existing ag.service | "ag.service already exists and differs from our template." | Radio: keep (default) / backup + replace / replace |

If Detection turned up no triggers, this screen is skipped entirely.

Buttons: **Back**, **Next** (→ Install Progress). "Abort" choices on
specific prompts route directly to a close-window action without
writing anything.

### Screen 4: Install Progress

Live during the actual install. Two panes:

- **Left:** the step list with check/x/spinner indicators, mirroring
  the bash installer's `[N/TOTAL] ► <step>` sequence:
  ```
  ✓ Ensure XDG tree           (0s)
  ✓ Seed config               (0s)
  ✓ Install artifacts         (3s)
  ⟳ FalkorDB native service   (4s — extracting binaries...)
    Systemd user units
    Health check
  ```
- **Right:** scrolling log view showing the install's structured log
  output (the same color-coded lines the bash installer writes to the
  log file). Auto-scrolls; user can scroll up to pin position.

A persistent footer shows elapsed time and a single line of "current
operation" status for users who don't want to read the log.

On step failure: the log auto-scrolls to the error, the left pane's
spinner becomes an X, and a modal opens with "Install failed — see
log. Open log file? / Retry? / Cancel?"

No "Back" button during this screen — writes are happening.

### Screen 5: First-Run Config

The new bit. Runs **after** all install steps complete (binary copied,
FalkorDB up, compose stack up, ag.service rendered + enabled but
**not yet started**). The form collects the few settings the user
needs to pick before ag's first boot. Everything else is left at
default and remains editable in the running dashboard's Config pages.

**Three knobs, all optional (defaults work):**

#### Ollama model

Only shown if Ollama is detected. Queries
`http://127.0.0.1:11434/api/tags` to populate a dropdown of models the
user has pulled. Default selection:
1. `phi:latest` if present
2. otherwise the first model returned
3. if no models: dropdown disabled, link to "ollama pull phi" docs

Writes the choice to `~/.config/ag/ag.env` as `OLLAMA_MODEL=<choice>`.

#### FalkorDB password

Text input, prefilled with `agpassword123` (the default). A yellow
warning chip below: "This is the default password — change it if this
host is ever exposed beyond localhost."

If the user changes it:
- Update `~/.config/ag/ag.env` `FALKOR_PASSWORD=<new>`
- Re-render `~/.config/systemd/user/falkordb.service` with the new
  `{{FDB_PASS}}` value
- `systemctl --user daemon-reload && systemctl --user restart falkordb.service`
- Validate with `redis-cli -p $FDB_PORT -a $new_pass ping` before
  proceeding

If they keep the default: no change.

#### Agent mode

Dropdown with the five modes from `backend/src/agent.rs`:

- `Hybrid` *(default)* — search + LLM fallback. The "just works" choice.
- `Rag` — retrieval only (no LLM; works without Ollama)
- `Llm` — LLM only (no retrieval; Ollama required)
- `RagStrict` — grounded retrieval only
- `Agentic` — Rig framework tool-calling loop

A one-line description per mode is shown below the dropdown when
hovered. Writes `AGENT_MODE=<choice>` to `ag.env`.

**After the form:** "Start ag now" button at the bottom right. On
click: `systemctl --user start ag.service`, then poll `/health` up to
~20s. Then → Screen 6.

### Screen 6: Done / Summary

The four-bucket summary from the bash installer, plus the launch
buttons:

```
✓ Reused silently        docker, ollama, ~/.cargo, target/, ag.env, libtika
✓ Reused confirmed       system-redis at :6379
+ Installed fresh        ag.service, ag-stack.service, falkordb.service,
                         ~/.local/bin/ag, web/, libtika
⚠ Reused with assumption system-redis auth not verified
                         — set REDIS_PASSWORD in ag.env if required
```

Plus the configured first-run settings:
```
Configured for first run:
   Ollama model     : phi:latest
   FalkorDB password: (default — consider changing)
   Agent mode       : Hybrid
   Backend port     : 3010
```

Buttons:
- **Open ag dashboard** → opens `http://127.0.0.1:3010` in the system
  browser
- **View install log** → opens the log file in the system editor
- **Close** → exits

## Architecture

```
ag/
  backend/                       (unchanged)
  frontend/fro/                  (unchanged)
  tools/memory_cli/              (unchanged)
  installer/                     ← new workspace member
    Cargo.toml                   (binary crate)
    src/
      main.rs                    Dioxus desktop entrypoint
      app.rs                     router + global state
      detection.rs               mirrors bash installer's detect_* fns,
                                 returns a typed DetectionResult
      install_steps.rs           sequential steps that actually write
                                 files (uses tokio::process for systemctl,
                                 std::fs for copies)
      first_run.rs               first-run config logic
                                 (Ollama API probe, env file writes,
                                 falkordb restart on password change)
      summary.rs                 builds the four-bucket summary from
                                 detection + step results
      bundled.rs                 declares include_bytes!-style references
                                 to the bundled assets (the AppImage's
                                 squashfs paths are visible at runtime
                                 via std::env::current_exe + ../usr/share)
      ui/
        welcome.rs               Screen 1
        detection_screen.rs      Screen 2
        prompts.rs               Screen 3
        progress.rs              Screen 4 (left pane + log view)
        first_run_form.rs        Screen 5
        summary_screen.rs        Screen 6
        components/              shared: buttons, list, log viewer,
                                 progress indicator
    assets/
      icon.png                   AppImage icon
      ag-installer.desktop       freedesktop entry for the AppImage
      style.css                  global app styles (mirrors the
                                 dashboard's color tokens)
  .github/
    workflows/
      release.yml                ← new
```

### `installer` ↔ bash installer ↔ ag relationship

- **bash installer** is the source-of-truth for the design (XDG layout,
  detection rules, prompt logic, three systemd units, reuse policy).
  Always works on a developer's machine with the repo checked out.
  Test-bed for new install behaviors before they land in the GUI.
- **GUI installer** is a parallel binary that **reimplements** the
  install logic in Rust. Same XDG layout, same detection rules
  (probably 1:1 ports of each `detect_*` function), same three systemd
  units. Does **not** shell out to `install-linux.sh` — too brittle to
  pipe progress.
- **ag itself** is the same binary either way. The GUI installer ships
  it pre-built; the bash installer builds it from source. The XDG
  install location is identical.

### Async / blocking model

Dioxus desktop is single-threaded for UI updates. All blocking I/O
(file copies, subprocess invocations, HTTP probes) runs on
`tokio::task::spawn_blocking` or `tokio::process::Command`, posts
progress via Dioxus signals, and never blocks the render thread.

The install-progress screen's log view is fed by a `tokio::sync::mpsc`
channel that step functions write to and the UI drains in a
`use_future` loop.

## CI release pipeline

A new workflow at `.github/workflows/release.yml`. Triggers:

- `push` of a tag matching `v*.*.*`
- Manual `workflow_dispatch` (for debugging)

Pipeline stages:

```
                                ┌─ cargo build --release --target x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu
                                │      (ag binary)
                                ├─ npm ci + npm run css:build + trunk build --release
                                │      (frontend dist)
                                ├─ docker pull falkordb/falkordb:<pinned> + extract
                                │      (FalkorDB binaries)
                                ├─ cargo build -p installer --release
                                │      (Dioxus desktop binary)
                                │
release.yml on Ubuntu 24.04 ─────┤
                                │
                                ├─ Assemble AppDir/
                                │      AppRun, ag-installer, usr/{bin,lib,share/ag}/
                                │
                                ├─ appimagetool AppDir/  →  ag-installer-vX.Y.Z-x86_64.AppImage
                                │
                                ├─ sha256sum the AppImage
                                │
                                └─ gh release create vX.Y.Z
                                        --notes-from-tag
                                        ag-installer-*.AppImage
                                        sha256sums.txt
```

### Why Ubuntu 24.04 specifically

Originally bin3 picked Ubuntu 22.04 (glibc 2.35) for maximum
backward-compat. That decision was revised on the first CI run
(`v0.1.0-dev2`, 2026-06-13) because ag's `onnx` default feature pulls
the `ort` crate, which **downloads prebuilt ONNX Runtime C++ binaries
that require glibc 2.39+** (they reference ISO C 23 symbols like
`__isoc23_strtol`). Building on 22.04 surfaced the mismatch at link
time; even with a workaround, the resulting AppImage wouldn't *run*
on 22.04 because the embedded ONNX binaries need 2.39.

Ubuntu 24.04 (glibc 2.39) is the actual baseline the codebase
already required. Distros covered:

- Ubuntu 24.04 LTS, 24.10
- Debian 13 (trixie) — releases mid-2026
- Fedora 39+
- Arch (rolling, current)
- RHEL 10 / Alma 10 / Rocky 10 — released mid-2026

**Distros explicitly NOT supported by the AppImage:**
Ubuntu 22.04 LTS, Debian 12 (bookworm), Fedora 38 and below, RHEL 9
and below. Users on those distros either upgrade or use the bash
installer (which builds from source against their local glibc).

This compatibility loss is bounded — Ubuntu 22.04's EOL is April 2027.

The decision could be reverted if ag drops the `onnx` default feature
or if the `ort` crate ships glibc-2.35-compatible prebuilts. Until
then, glibc 2.39 is honest.

For now: x86_64 only. arm64 is a Phase 2 addition (cross-compile or
self-hosted ARM runner; both add complexity worth deferring until
demand exists).

### Versioning

Semver. Tags are `vMAJOR.MINOR.PATCH`. **Starting version: `v0.1.0`**
(Phase 0 decision — no pre-release tags; ship `v1.0.0` only when Phase H
acceptance criteria are met). Each successive release bumps PATCH for
bug fixes, MINOR for new features, MAJOR only when behavior changes
break existing installs.

The installer binary surfaces its version via:
- `ag-installer --version` (CLI flag for sanity-checking the AppImage)
- A footer on every screen
- The Welcome screen explicitly

The ag binary inside the AppImage gets the same version embedded via
`build.rs` (this is **the** Phase 2 deferral from `bin2` made
concrete — the GUI installer's release pipeline is what justifies
finally adding `build.rs`).

`ag --version` will print:
```
ag 0.1.0
git: a1b2c3d
built: 2026-06-13T12:34:56Z (ubuntu-24.04)
```

The installer compares against `ag-installer --version` on launch to
confirm the bundle is consistent.

### Auto-update check

The installer queries
`https://api.github.com/repos/<owner>/ag/releases/latest` on launch
(default — stable releases only; pre-releases are filtered out by the
endpoint), compares against its own version, and shows a non-blocking
banner if a newer AppImage exists. Click → opens the GitHub Release
page. We do NOT auto-download/install — too much trust to ask for in
v1.

Opt-in `--include-prereleases` flag instead polls `/releases` and
takes the topmost tag with `draft=false`. Useful for early testers
who want to track development builds.

The check result is cached in `~/.cache/ag-installer/last-check.json`
for 4 hours so the launch doesn't always pay the network round-trip
(and to stay well under the 60-req/hour unauthenticated rate limit on
api.github.com).

## What goes in `~/.config/ag/ag.env` after first-run

The bash installer seeds `ag.env` from `.env.example` and applies
flag-driven overrides. The GUI installer does the same plus the
first-run config form's choices. Concretely, after the first-run
config screen has been submitted, these lines are guaranteed to
reflect the user's choices:

```
BACKEND_HOST=127.0.0.1
BACKEND_PORT=<from port prompt or default 3010>
OLLAMA_URL=http://127.0.0.1:11434
OLLAMA_MODEL=<from first-run dropdown>
FALKOR_URI=redis://localhost:<port>
FALKOR_PASSWORD=<from first-run input or default>
AGENT_MODE=<from first-run dropdown>
REDIS_URL=<from system-redis prompt or default>
```

Every other env key is left at the `.env.example` default. They're
editable in the dashboard's Config → Runtime page (`/config/runtime`)
afterward — the runtime settings layer (`docs/runtime-config.md`)
handles those without restart for the 13 hot-reloadable keys.

## Detection rules — reuse from `bin2`

The GUI installer's `detection.rs` implements the same set of
detections as the bash installer's `detect_existing_state`. Listed
here for the implementer's convenience; full rationale in `bin2`:

| Detection | How |
|---|---|
| Docker present | `which docker` (Rust: `std::process::Command::new("which").arg("docker")`) |
| Ollama active | `systemctl --user is-active ollama` + `GET http://127.0.0.1:11434/api/tags` returns 200 |
| Compose stack up | `docker compose ls` parses to JSON, look for `name=ag` |
| FalkorDB healthy | `systemctl --user is-active falkordb.service` + `redis-cli ping` returns `PONG` |
| `ag.env` exists | `Path::new("~/.config/ag/ag.env").exists()` |
| Backend port busy | parse `ss -tln` output, look for `:$PORT` listener |
| System Redis on 6379 | `redis-cli -p 6379 ping` returns `PONG` AND no `ag-redis` docker container running |
| Native observability | `systemctl --user is-active loki|tempo|otelcol` for each |
| `ag.service` drift | file exists, hash differs from rendered template |
| Low RAM | `/proc/meminfo` `MemTotal` < 8 GB |
| Disk free | `statfs` on `$HOME` and the AppImage's mount point |

All detections run on the **Detection** screen in parallel
(`tokio::join!`) and complete in well under a second on a normal box.
A loading spinner shows during.

## Phasing (summary)

8 weeks total: A Foundation → B GUI scaffold → C Detection+prompts →
D Real install → E First-run config → F Release pipeline polish →
G Multi-distro verify → H Polish+a11y. **See §Detailed execution
plan** below for the dependency DAG, key risks, and per-phase tasks /
acceptance criteria.

## Things we're deferring out of v1

- **arm64 builds.** Need either cross-compile or a self-hosted ARM
  runner. Wait until someone asks.
- **macOS / Windows.** Same toolchain choices (Dioxus desktop works
  cross-platform), but ag itself needs work to run on those — not the
  installer's problem to solve.
- **Auto-update that downloads + installs.** Just notify in v1.
- **Code signing.** Sigstore / GPG signing of the AppImage. Worth doing
  before any real user adoption; not before v1.
- **Flathub / Snap / .deb / .rpm.** Add later if AppImage isn't
  enough. The AppImage approach doesn't preclude these.
- **Telemetry / phone-home.** Don't.

## Open questions for review

1. Is "First-Run Config inside the GUI" the right UX, or would a
   separate `ag-setup` CLI tool be cleaner? (Current take: inside the
   GUI is right because it's the one screen the user will visit
   exactly once. A separate tool re-introduces a CLI step.)
2. Should the installer offer to install desktop-environment
   integration (a `.desktop` file under `~/.local/share/applications/`
   pointing at `xdg-open http://127.0.0.1:3010`) on the last screen?
   Useful for "click an icon to open ag" but trivial. (Lean: yes,
   minor.)
3. Should `ag-installer --uninstall` be a thing, or does the user run
   `installers/uninstall-linux.sh`? AppImage convention says the
   AppImage itself manages uninstall. (Lean: add an `--uninstall`
   flag that drives the same logic as the bash uninstaller.)
4. The first-run config screen is described as "three knobs." Are
   there others that genuinely need to be set before first run?
   Candidates: `TRUST_PROXY` (no — leave at false), `RUST_LOG` (no —
   info is fine), `OTEL_TRACES_ENABLED` (no — observability stack
   handles it). Confirm the three-knob scope is right.

## Detailed execution plan (8 weeks)

The phasing table above is the sketch; this section is the plan. Each
phase lists concrete tasks (with file paths), dependencies, risks, and
the commit shape at end-of-phase. Treat as the working punch list —
update it as work proceeds.

### Dependency graph

```mermaid
graph LR
  P0[Phase 0: Pre-flight] --> A[A: Foundation<br/>installer crate + AppImage CI]
  A --> B[B: GUI scaffold<br/>six screens, mock data]
  A --> C[C: Detection + prompts]
  B --> D[D: Real install]
  C --> D
  D --> E[E: First-run config]
  D --> G[G: Multi-distro verify]
  E --> F[F: Release pipeline polish]
  G --> H[H: Polish + a11y]
  F --> H
```

**Critical path** = P0 → A → B → D → E → F → H (~7 weeks if walked
serially). Phase C is in parallel with B once Phase A is done. Phase G
can begin partway through D (verify bash installer on the five distros
as a baseline; re-verify with the AppImage path once E lands). Phase F
gates final ship because the auto-update banner needs the release
pipeline before H tags v1.0.0.

### Key risks across all phases

- **Dioxus desktop maturity.** As of early 2026 it's usable but less
  battle-tested than Tauri. Track Dioxus releases; if a serious bug
  blocks Phase B or C, the fallback is to swap to Tauri at the cost
  of ~1 week of port work.
- **GitHub Actions minutes.** Tag-driven builds on a public repo are
  free; if the repo goes private, ~$0.008/min adds up at ~30 min per
  build. Track usage.
- **glibc compatibility.** Ubuntu 24.04 build (glibc 2.39) runs on
  Ubuntu 24.04+, Debian 13+, Fedora 39+, RHEL 10+. Ubuntu 22.04 /
  Debian 12 / Fedora 38 / RHEL 9 are NOT supported by the AppImage
  because ag's `onnx` feature requires glibc 2.39 via prebuilt
  ONNX Runtime binaries. Document, don't try to support older
  glibc — users on older distros use the bash installer.
- **AppImage user-experience pitfalls.** First-time AppImage users
  often miss the `chmod +x` step. README needs to cover it clearly;
  the `.desktop` integration on the last screen helps.

The per-phase risks below are *specific* risks unique to that phase;
these four cut across all of them and inform the cross-phase fallback
plan (swap toolkit, cap CI use, drop a distro from support, refine
the README).

